[{'text': 'People seem to love stuff like bungee jumping
and sky-diving.', 'start': 0.089, 'duration': 2.84}, {'text': 'But what draws us to these scary life-threatening
experiences?', 'start': 2.929, 'duration': 3.841}, {'text': 'Why do we want to jump off of stuff?', 'start': 6.77, 'duration': 4.27}, {'text': 'On May 16, 2015, Dean Potter, a celebrated
extreme sportsman, and a fellow climber, Graham', 'start': 11.04, 'duration': 10.45}, {'text': 'Hunt; jumped off a 7,500 foot (2,285m) cliff
in Yosemite National Park with the goal of', 'start': 21.49, 'duration': 4.959}, {'text': 'wingsuit flying through the rocky cliffs before
parachuting to safety.', 'start': 26.449, 'duration': 4.151}, {'text': 'Both men crashed while trying to fly through
an outcropping and were found dead many hours', 'start': 30.6, 'duration': 4.96}, {'text': 'later.', 'start': 35.56, 'duration': 1.0}, {'text': 'BASE jumping is an acronym for buildings,
antennas, spans (such as bridges) and Earth', 'start': 36.56, 'duration': 4.519}, {'text': '(cliffs and mountaintops) -- all places to
jump from while wearing a wingsuit, parachute', 'start': 41.079, 'duration': 5.0}, {'text': 'or both.', 'start': 46.079, 'duration': 1.0}, {'text': 'At least 257 people have died BASE jumping
to date, according to a major BASE jumping', 'start': 47.079, 'duration': 4.791}, {'text': 'forum; and Potter, who was a major enthusiast
for outdoor "extreme" sports, called BASE', 'start': 51.87, 'duration': 5.15}, {'text': 'jumping and free-climbing, "death-consequence"
activities.', 'start': 57.02, 'duration': 3.969}, {'text': "Aren't we all programmed to survive?", 'start': 60.989, 'duration': 2.301}, {'text': 'Why do we risk death for a thrill?', 'start': 63.29, 'duration': 2.529}, {'text': 'More than 800 people have died climbing the
mountains of Nepal -- including Everest,;', 'start': 65.819, 'duration': 4.631}, {'text': '442 from skydiving from 1998 to 2014 - and
even scuba-diving sees about 80 deaths annually.', 'start': 70.45, 'duration': 7.0}, {'text': 'I mean, skateboarding had 30 deaths in 2012!', 'start': 77.45, 'duration': 3.86}, {'text': 'Psychologists believe we perform risky behaviors
because of our fear response, and medical', 'start': 81.31, 'duration': 4.969}, {'text': "researchers believe it has to do with the
brain's reward systems; though both are true.", 'start': 86.279, 'duration': 3.45}, {'text': 'In a small study from the Queensland University
of Technology in Australia; researchers explored', 'start': 89.729, 'duration': 4.041}, {'text': 'the psychological result of fear responses
in extreme sports participants.', 'start': 93.77, 'duration': 4.619}, {'text': 'Fear is an important inborn response to perceived
danger.', 'start': 98.389, 'duration': 2.851}, {'text': "Your body's top priority is to preserve itself;
fear is a way to motivate it to do so.", 'start': 101.24, 'duration': 4.499}, {'text': 'But for some people, overcoming fear was a
meaningful and constructive event in their', 'start': 105.739, 'duration': 6.16}, {'text': 'lives.', 'start': 111.899, 'duration': 1.0}, {'text': "They still EXPERIENCE fear, but it's not seen
as a negative, but rather, a positive experience.", 'start': 112.899, 'duration': 5.871}, {'text': 'Potter wrote specifically, and poetically,
about his experiences with fear, and how overcoming', 'start': 118.77, 'duration': 4.769}, {'text': 'that fear was transformative for him.', 'start': 123.539, 'duration': 2.47}, {'text': "Unfortunately, that's not easily translatable
for a general population -- instead we can", 'start': 126.009, 'duration': 5.581}, {'text': 'only look at how the chemicals in our brains
surrounding fear go on to affect our behavior.', 'start': 131.59, 'duration': 5.119}, {'text': 'When jumping out of an airplane or free-climbing
up a cliff, an almond-shaped set of neurons', 'start': 136.709, 'duration': 4.801}, {'text': 'in our brain called the amygdala releases
hormones which quicken the heart, hone the', 'start': 141.51, 'duration': 4.339}, {'text': 'senses and prepare your body to flee or fight.', 'start': 145.849, 'duration': 4.42}, {'text': "During this fear response, our brains' reward
center releases large amounts of dopamine.", 'start': 150.269, 'duration': 5.25}, {'text': 'Studies have shown, dopamine, a powerful reward
chemical for our bodies, is also connected', 'start': 155.519, 'duration': 5.09}, {'text': 'to the recollection of terror.', 'start': 160.609, 'duration': 2.21}, {'text': "It's released when we eat, exercise, or talk
to our friends and family, and reinforces", 'start': 162.819, 'duration': 4.79}, {'text': 'those healthy behaviors by making us feel
good about doing those things.', 'start': 167.609, 'duration': 5.19}, {'text': 'But, massive dopamine release is associated
with drug use, and addiction; which is how', 'start': 172.799, 'duration': 5.861}, {'text': 'extreme athletes and enthusiasts are often
associated with junkies or addicts.', 'start': 178.66, 'duration': 5.35}, {'text': 'Extreme athletes provoke this fear response
in themselves, experiencing the fear of death,', 'start': 184.01, 'duration': 4.83}, {'text': 'and enjoying the natural-high they get from
the dopamine release that follows.', 'start': 188.84, 'duration': 4.63}, {'text': 'The problem is, the brain can get used to

language created to describe heavy-use drug', 'start': 202.7, 'duration': 4.56}, {'text': 'addicts.', 'start': 207.26, 'duration': 1.0}, {'text': 'A 2004 study compared ecstasy-users to bungee-jumpers
and found similar sensation-seeking brain', 'start': 208.26, 'duration': 5.61}, {'text': 'chemistry.', 'start': 213.87, 'duration': 1.0}, {'text': 'The reason people continue to do these activities,
aside from them being fun and making them', 'start': 214.87, 'duration': 3.66}, {'text': "feel good, is once their brain gets acclimated
to higher levels of dopamine, it's difficult", 'start': 218.53, 'duration': 5.25}, {'text': 'to wean it off.', 'start': 223.78, 'duration': 1.429}, {'text': 'Like an addict, the brain craves MORE dopamine
